  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for combating money laundering\n- Provides guidelines and recommendations for countries\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigation and prosecution\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Establishes money laundering as a criminal offense\n- Provides framework for international legal cooperation\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets standards for banking regulations to prevent money laundering\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n6. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish common rules across EU member states for preventing money laundering\n\nThese laws generally require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting requirements\n- Establish legal frameworks for investigation\n- Promote international cooperation\n- Implement strict due diligence procedures in financial institutions\n\nMost developed countries have domestic laws aligned with these international standards.",
